20. Verona - Coach Salvatore Bocchetti - who is already the Gialloblu's second coach this season - is under pressure. Not entirely unjustifiably so. Verona are not doing well and are heading for hopeless relegation.

19. Sampdoria - The Blucerchiati already reinforced themselves this winter with Sam Lammers and Bram Nuytinck. Led by Dejan Stankovic, the Dutch duo must make sure Samp does not get relegated. A very difficult task.

18. Cremonese - Cyriel Dessers' side have yet to win a single Serie A match this season. Not exactly fortunate that the first game after the stop is against Juventus. At the slightest misstep, coach Alvini - who is waiting for attacking reinforcements - flies out of the job.

17. Spezia - Due to Bartlomiej Dragowski's injury, Jeroen Zoet is Spezia's first goalkeeper for the time being after the winter break. Even with the former PSV player between the stick, it is bound to be a long battle against relegation.

16. Lecce - Lecce actually managed to win two games in a row before the winter break. With wins over Atalanta and Sampdoria, the team from beautiful Puglia climbed to 16th place. That is no bad thing.

15. Sassuolo - Fifteenth place is simply not good enough for Sassuolo. The Neroverdi lost several star players last summer, and it is reflected in the results. Coach Dionisi must turn it around or his time in Reggio Emilia will be done next summer.

14. Monza - With Raffaele Palladino as new coach, Monza finally managed to open the hunt for the top ten before the winter break. For now, Berlusconi's team is 9 points above the relegation line. So they may - and should - look upwards.

13. Empoli - It is a pity Mattia Destro is still injured for a while, otherwise Empoli could have fielded the most beautiful attacking duo in Serie A after the winter break. Indeed, Ciccio Caputo returned to the old nest and should provide the goals.

12. Salernitana - For now, Salernitana manage to continue last season's fairytale. Although not everyone is happy in Campania, 12th place is great and Mexican goalkeeper Ochoa has already arrived. It is very much hoping that Spaniard Isco will join him there.

11. Bologna - The Rossoblu are in their familiar 11th spot. Before the winter break, Thiago Motta's team won 4 of its last 5 games. That's not bad at all. Time for that - led by Arnautovic and in memory of former coach Mihajlovic - to continue.

10. Fiorentina - So far, Fiorentina's season has been rather disappointing. Although coach Italiano most likely will eventually straighten it out, La Viola has been very shaky so far. This is reflected in the meagre points total in the league table.

9. Torino - With Ivan Juric, Torino have one of the best coaches in Serie A. Although the selection is nothing to write home about and the best player was sold, the Granata are in a handsome 9th place and lead 'the best of the rest'.

8. Udinese - Udinese started the season very well and for a while were even in a spot that entitled them to Champions League football. Unfortunately, the Zebrette did not win after 3 October and it is to be hoped for them that the free fall will not continue.

7. Roma - For the Giallorossi, seventh place is simply not good enough. After Dybala's arrival, the title was briefly dreamt of. After the Argentine got injured, those hopes quickly ebbed away. Like Wijnaldum, the fresh world champion will be back soon.

6. Atalanta - The Orobici were on a good run, but lost 4 of the past 5 duels, so sixth place will still feel painful. After the winter break, the hope is that the vicissitudes will be put to bed.

The Athletic asked some anonymous questions to top recruits
https://theathletic.com/4044579/2023/01/03/college-football-recruiting-nil-2/

>What was the largest amount of NIL money discussed with you by a coach or NIL representative?

Player 1: $400K a year. It was surprising, for sure, playing defensive back.

Player 2: I never had money tossed my way in any conversations.

Player 3: Somebody tried to throw $1 million at me on signing day. Somebody called my parents and coaches. My loyalty to the program I signed with isn’t worth a million dollars. I’ll make that in no time.

Player 4: I don’t want to answer that one. It was more than $1 million.

Player 5: (One) school mentioned $3.2 million over four years.

Player 8: Nobody talked NIL with me or threw money at me.

Player 10: Over seven figures. It wasn’t the coaches. It was a guy who did NIL stuff. The closer I got to the commitment, the more and more things went up.

Player 11: You’re going to look at me like I’m dumb. It was $75,000, a car and my own apartment. But I know you are not getting money if you’re bad. The school introduces you to the people who are going to pay you.

Player 12: Numbers didn’t come up, but (a few schools) talked about what I could get. Schools knew that wasn’t going to attract me, though, so they didn’t talk about it much.

Player 13: The biggest amount of money was $3 million over four years. You want to get paid for your results. It played a factor, but not as big as some people think.

Player 14: There were some big numbers, but nothing specific. It was like between $50K and $75K. With the game nowadays, it’s normal. Those prices can range depending on how much of an impact you make with the program.

Player 15: I didn’t have any numbers float my way. I had a bond with the coach and made my decision based off that.

>Where did NIL rank in your decision-making process: first, second or third? And if it didn’t finish first, what other factors were more important?

Player 1: It finished third. No. 1 was player development.

Player 2: It was second or third. I didn’t really know much about NIL, but it played a role. The only thing more important for me was the relationships with the coaches. You have to bond with them.

Player 3: Last. Relationships, player development were No. 1 and No. 2.

Player 4: It was third. To me, relationships and a school that was going to develop me were the first two. Then a scheme that fits me best.

Player 5: Third. NIL will help me feed my family and keep money in my pocket. Education and football, though, were No. 1 and No. 2.

Player 6: Third. Academics first, the coaching staff and the system I was going to play in were next.

Player 7: Third, really. I just want to play football. I know NIL is a big part of the world now. But I was thinking long-term.

Player 8: Third for me. Academics were No. 1 and then stuff on the field.

Player 9: It was second for me. I want to make money in college, but I know making the NFL is the best way to get paid.

Player 10: Third. Relationships and player development were first and second.

Player 11: Third. If you’re not playing well, you don’t make any money. Everybody knows that. It’s the system that fits me and my playing style, where I’m comfortable, can grow as a player and make the NFL. I need a coach that’s going to keep it a buck with me all the time.

Player 12: Definitely last. I just wanted to go somewhere I could get properly developed.

Player 13: Third. Development, the environment and the people I’ll be around are more important.

Player 14: It wasn’t first, second or third. It played no role for me. It was all about culture, the championship tradition. We all know the money is going to come.

Player 15: Probably third. Playing time was No. 1 for me as a freshman.

It depends. If it's a bigger team than you, talk them up for sure because you want them to not be motivated. If they're small you need your squad to guard against complacency but also not feel pressure (obviously this one is a little bit trickier). You need to know your squad for those. Mine right now can't handle any kind of pressure and doesn't get complacent much so I project confidence. It's basically just an extension of the team talk that the other team can hear too. It really depends on your situation and the other team's. If the other manager compliments me I usually call it condescending. If I have a good streak going against another team/manager I ALWAYS use the one that says the other team has the pressure to end it. If I have a losing streak vs them the one that sucks the Manager's dick (he's one of the best managers in the game and that's a level I've yet to reach) seems to work often enough. It doesn't like guarantee you a win but sometimes it has a noticeable effect where some CL team will play like shit against you or whatever. Usually I avoid talking about opposition players individually though unless they have a shit personality. Bottom line is you can dictate the narrative by only answering the ones you want to be the story and if you're not sure, just go fully neutral

On October 24, 1971, the Lions hosted the Chicago Bears at Tiger Stadium. Late in the 4th quarter, with Detroit trailing 28–23, the Lions were driving into Chicago territory and Hughes, who entered the game as an injury replacement, caught a pass from quarterback Greg Landry for 32 yards and a first down at the Bears' 37-yard line.

Three plays later, Landry threw a pass that tight end Charlie Sanders dropped near the end zone. Hughes, a decoy on the play, began running back to the huddle with 1:02 showing on the clock. Suddenly, he dropped to the turf clutching his chest around the 20-yard line.[3] Hughes collapsed near Bears linebacker Dick Butkus, who saw him begin to convulse violently on the field. Butkus motioned to the sideline frantically to get Hughes assistance.[6]

Both teams' doctors and trainers, along with a physician who happened to be attending the game, ran to Hughes to try to save him. An ambulance was called for and arrived to take Hughes to Henry Ford Hospital, where he was pronounced dead at 5:34 pm that afternoon. He was 28 years old. The game was played to its conclusion in front of a now-stunned silent crowd in Tiger Stadium, with the Bears' lead holding. The Lions awaited word of Hughes' condition after the game and the players were informed once word had broken that he was dead.
